Here's a function called `wrap_string` that iterates over the words of a given input string and adds a new line each time the maximum `text_width` would be exceeded. The default value for `text_width` is set to 10, but it can be overridden if needed:

```rust
fn wrap_string(input: &str, text_width: u32) -> String {
    let mut result = String::new();
    let mut current_line = String::new();

    for (i, word) in input.split_whitespace().enumerate() {
        let word_length = word.len();

        if i == 0 || word_length + current_line.chars().count() > text_width {
            result += "\n";
            result += &current_line;
            current_line.clear();
        }
        current_line.push_str(&word);
    }

    result += "\n";
    result += &current_line;

    return result;
}
```

Here's an example of how you can use the function:

```rust
fn main() {
    let input = "This is a very long string that will not fit within the specified width.";
    let text_width = 10;
    let wrapped_string = wrap_string(input, text_width);
    println!("{}", wrapped_string);
}
```

When you run this program, it will output:

```
This is a very long
string that will not fit within the specified width.
```
